                title: "Will my heel pain get better?",
                content: [
                    {
                        text: "In the vast majority of cases, yes. Plantar fasciitis is usually self-limiting: it tends to settle with time. Many people improve even without formal treatment, but the right basics — stretching, supportive footwear, and sensible load — usually speed things up. There are no magic cures; boring consistency beats dramatic one-off treatments.",
                    },
                ],
            },
            {
                title: "Why is the first step in the morning so painful?",
                content: [
                    {
                        text: "This is a classic feature. After rest, the plantar fascia and calf can stiffen overnight. The first few steps stretch tissues that have shortened while you were off your feet, which causes a sharp pain that often eases as you get moving. A slow toe stretch before standing, supportive shoes from the first step, and daily calf stretching (especially on a slant board) often help — see ",
                    },
                    {
                        text: "Stage 1: Foundation",
                        href: "/guide/plantar-fasciitis/stage-1",
